{"id":14880949,"mediaExerciseId":"f5a3f9b8-e748-426a-9464-906137c23dbb","exerciseName":"11","chapterName":"6","chapterTitle":"Discounted Cash Flow Valuation","groupId":612301,"groupTitle":"Questions and Problems","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":184,"solutions":[{"id":5967595,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In the previous exercise, we determined the cost of the perpetuity of the insurance offered by the Maybe Pay Life Insurance Co., the cash payment is an annual $35,000 to be received forever at a rate of return of 4.7%.\n\nIn this exercise, If we are to assume the cost of the policy at $800,000, we will determine the fair interest rate for the deal.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"A fair interest rate should be based on the present value of the policy and the annual payments; the cost should weigh on the benefit. Hence, to determine the fair rate in this calculation, we will divide the annual payments by the perpetual annuity present value. Our calculation can be summarized in the following equation:\n\n$$ \\begin{aligned}\n\\text{Intrerest Rate} &=\\dfrac{PMT}{PV}\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\nWhere:\n\n$PMT$, which refers to the annual payments\n$PV$, which represent the present value\n\n\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":392,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/ad25a12d00899a14877ed8024c663454/1dd64388af5d1594cd7f41ff5dc40e07/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":197,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/ad25a12d00899a14877ed8024c663454/1dd64388af5d1594cd7f41ff5dc40e07/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"Let's now calculate the interest rate.\n\n$$ \\begin{aligned}\n\\text{Intrerest Rate} &=\\dfrac{\\$35,000}{\\$800,000}\n\\\\[10pt]\n&= \\boxed{\\bf{4.38\\%}}\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\n**Therefore, if the cost of the policy is $800,000 and the perpetuity payment is $35,000, a reasonable interest rate is 4.38%**","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"ef5f69d9-3a24-4a58-bc5c-768ebce8afeb","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":3}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14880950,"exerciseName":"12","page":184,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"f68e1a78-4603-458e-adf1-a51b27de10b0","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-6-questions-and-problems-12-f68e1a78-4603-458e-adf1-a51b27de10b0"},{"id":14880951,"exerciseName":"13","page":184,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"ab3f94b8-b7dc-4275-bf99-b2728ce78578","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-6-questions-and-problems-13-ab3f94b8-b7dc-4275-bf99-b2728ce78578"}],"previousExercises":[{"id":14880948,"exerciseName":"10","page":184,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"905135ea-abda-4916-94b0-ae420e12de4e","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-f